{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17488345","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17488345"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T03:38:03+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T03:38:03+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"417"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"417","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/417"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.02,0.29,0.53,0.12,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"417"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96661"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"417","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/417"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"417"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79296"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"674"},{"type":"tags","id":"1115"},{"type":"tags","id":"4955"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11629"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"7343"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7763"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33143"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42080"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96661","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/96661"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 32-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a painless swelling on the dorsum of her left index finger. This has been present for six weeks and has grown rapidly during this time. She reports that it bleeds easily when touched. There is no history of trauma or any other obvious precipitating factor. She has no significant medical history. Her only medication is an oral contraceptive pill which she started three months ago. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. The lesion is visualised on her left index finger (Image). The lesion has a moist surface and bleeds on minimal contact.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Melanoma","Cherry haemangioma","Pyogenic granuloma","Strawberry haemangioma","Arteriovenous malformation"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis case presents a classic example of \u003Cstrong\u003Epyogenic granuloma\u003C/strong\u003E (also known as lobular capillary haemangioma), a benign vascular lesion of the skin and mucosa. The clinical presentation of a rapidly growing, bright red, friable nodule that bleeds easily is highly characteristic. Pyogenic granulomas typically develop over a period of weeks, stabilising as a raised, reddish nodule ranging from a few millimetres to several centimetres in size. The patient\u0027s recent initiation of oral contraceptive pills is relevant, as hormonal changes are a recognised trigger for pyogenic granulomas. Other precipitating factors include minor trauma, pregnancy, certain medications (oral retinoids, protease inhibitors, immunosuppressants), and infections with organisms such as \u003Cem\u003EStaphylococcus aureus\u003C/em\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E\n\n\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMelanoma\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents as a pigmented lesion with features described by the ABCDE criteria: Asymmetry, irregular Border, Color variations (especially red, white, and blue tones in a brown or black lesion), Diameter greater than 6 mm, and Evolving or Elevated surface. The bright red appearance and rapid growth pattern in this case are not typical features of melanoma, which usually presents as a pigmented lesion with irregular borders and colour variation.\u003C/p\u003E\n\n\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECherry haemangioma\u003C/strong\u003E is the most common cutaneous vascular proliferation, typically appearing as tiny cherry-red papules or macules. They are usually multiple, small (1-5 mm), and develop in the third or fourth decades of life. Cherry haemangiomas are stable lesions that do not grow rapidly or bleed easily as seen in this case. They also tend to be darker red or purple rather than the bright red of pyogenic granulomas.\u003C/p\u003E\n\n\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStrawberry haemangioma\u003C/strong\u003E (infantile haemangioma) is a benign vascular tumour that typically appears in infancy, usually within the first few weeks of life. They undergo a proliferative phase followed by spontaneous involution over years. The patient\u0027s age and the acute onset in adulthood make this diagnosis unlikely. Additionally, strawberry haemangiomas have a characteristic appearance with a raised, bright red, lobulated surface resembling a strawberry.\u003C/p\u003E\n\n\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EArteriovenous malformation\u003C/strong\u003E (AVM) is an abnormal tangle of blood vessels connecting arteries and veins, which disrupts normal blood flow and oxygen circulation. AVMs are typically congenital, present from birth, and grow proportionally with the patient. They usually present as warm, pulsatile masses with a palpable thrill or audible bruit. The acute onset, small size, and lack of pulsatility in this case make an AVM unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Pyogenic granuloma is a benign vascular lesion that typically presents as a rapidly growing, friable, red nodule that bleeds easily.","Pyogenic granulomas are associated with hormonal changes, minor trauma, and certain medications including oral contraceptive pills."],"references":["Wollina U, Langner D, Fran\u00e7a K, Gianfaldoni S, Lotti T, Tchernev G. Pyogenic Granuloma - A Common Benign Vascular Tumor with Variable Clinical Presentation: New Findings and Treatment Options. Open Access Maced J Med Sci. 2017 Jul 13;5(4):423-426. Available at: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC5535648/","Patrice SJ, Wiss K, Mulliken JB. Pyogenic granuloma (lobular capillary hemangioma): a clinicopathologic study of 178 cases. Pediatr Dermatol. 1991 Dec. 8(4):267-76. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/1792196/","Mills SE, Cooper PH, Fechner RE. Lobular capillary hemangioma: the underlying lesion of pyogenic granuloma. A study of 73 cases from the oral and nasal mucous membranes. Am J Surg Pathol. 1980 Oct;4(5):470-9. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/7435775/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79296"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"417"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"18561"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"18561","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/18561"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/68ca6ffb-0042-4068-9dff-85e0a67cea9a.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/68ca6ffb-0042-4068-9dff-85e0a67cea9a.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":587,"height":371}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79296","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/79296"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-02T15:28:45+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-06T14:28:15+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"417"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96661"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"3","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/3"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddf4","name":"Dermatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:42+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups